us and british government officials have 
suspended negotiations on efforts by united airlines and american 
airlines for landing rights at londons heathrow airport 
there was no date for resumption of the talks which were held 
thursday and friday 
cyril murphy director of international operations for 
chiagobased united no progress was made in the negotiations 
british law has barred new entrants from congested heathrow 
since 1977 and diverted them to londons gatwick and other british 
airports 
many airlines have been clamoring for access to heathrow which 
is served by the london subway system and offers more air 
connections to europe and elsewhere 
fort worth texasbased american seeks to buy twas london and 
other overseas routes for 445 million united agreed in october to 
buy most of pan ams london routes for 400 million 
both airlines have said the deals wont proceed unless they gain 
access to heathrow 
an air services agreement allows successors to existing us 
airlines to assume their heathrow rights united and american say 
they qualify 
a spokesman for the british department of transport who spoke 
on anonymity said british officials offered to resume meetings 
next month 
</TEXT>
