<TEXT>
the deceptively alertlooking eyesopen 
unconciousness that envelops nancy cruzan and perhaps 10000 
other americans is difficult for families of the patients to 
accept 
in the condition called persistent vegetative state the eyes 
move about and sometimes react to sound patients may grimace 
smack their lips and seem to smile they sleep and wake up 
but these are simply reflexes the patients have permanent brain 
damage that prevents consciousness 
theyre just as unconscious as patients in a coma in which 
eyes are closed and the patient cannot be aroused said dr ron 
cranford an expert on persistent vegetative states 
it looks like theyre perfectly normal so its very hard 
on the family and health care providers to accept the fact that 
theyre not there 
it takes months or years for a family to come to terms with that 
and the lack of hope for recovery said cranford a neurologist at 
the hennepin county medical center in minneapolis 
a vegetative state is called persistent if there is no hope of 
recovery a person may still recover fully after six months to a 
year in a vegetative state if it was caused by a head injury 
especially in children cranford said 
but if the patient suffered loss of blood or oxygen to the 
brain as cruzan did recovery can be ruled out after one to three 
months he said 
cruzans condition has persisted since a 1983 auto accident 
last friday her feeding tube was removed after a lengthy court 
battle doctors said she would die from dehydration within a week 
or two of the tubes removal 
shes not in pain shes not suffering in any way because 
the brain centers that would let her perceive pain and suffering 
are destroyed said cranford who has examined her 
in her last two to three days she will go into a coma and then 
shell die a quiet peaceful death he said 
if death is inevitable in such cases why not give a lethal 
injection and get it over with sparing the family a long death 
watch 
that is homicide notes robert veatch director of the kennedy 
institute of ethics at georgetown university the question of 
legalization will draw much more serious debate in the coming 
decade he said 
one argument against legalization suggests that if it is allowed 
for a clearcut case it will then be allowed later for more shaky 
cases so that all sorts of people are getting killed that 
shouldnt be he said 
that fear is at least worth worrying about veatch said 
another argument is the idea that its simply wrong to kill in 
these situations even if it is ethically acceptable to let 
somebody die he said 
many people may have a gut feeling that there is a difference 
he said but it is not clear whether that reaction occurs because 
there really is a difference or because people have been taught 
all their lives that there is one he said 
that question will be debated in upcoming years but for now 
i think the difference is worthy of very serious consideration 
veatch said 
arthur caplan director of the center for biomedical ethics at 
the university of minnesota said he sees no ethical reason to 
hasten cruzans death for the sake of others 
no one said that death is supposed to be easy on other 
people he said 
</TEXT>
