hippie icon wavy gravy was right when he 
predicted recently that the 1990s will be like the 1960s turned 
upside down and inside out a survey of stanford university 
students suggests 
two stanford anthropologists who have surveyed student attitudes 
for 38 years predict that the 1990s may resemble the vietnam war 
era with a rise in extremism on both ends of the political 
spectrum 
i wouldnt be surprised if there was a fairly substantial form 
of radicalism said george spindler who along with his wife 
louise has queried stanford students each year since harry truman 
was president 
an upsurge in extreme rightwing views will occur because the 
middleclass feels increasingly threatened by societal 
uncertainties and minorities the spindlers say 
leftist extremism could rise from the threat of war in the 
middle east and the specter of recession they said 
the survey indicated increased tension among young adults and 
middleaged people the survey with 24 openended statements was 
given to students aged 17 to 45 
from several hundred to 4000 people have responded each year 
since 1952 
different eras show marked changes in attitudes in the 1950s a 
majority of respondents completed the statement the future 
is with rosy or a similar positive word the spindlers 
said 
today most said the future is dismal or something to 
worry about they said 
but black chicano and asian respondents didnt seem as insecure 
about the future as their white counterparts 
george spindler conceded the survey of of elite college students 
may not fully reflect the views of average americans 
but university populations set the trend he said then it 
filters down and causes changes in other populations 
