<TEXT>
an extensive western review of the soviet 
economy maps a bold strategy for a break with 70 years of 
government control but whether mikhail gorbachev can carry out the 
reforms is very much an open question 
the study commissioned by the leaders of the united states and 
six other western powers called for soviet citizens already 
suffering from shortages of food and other basic goods to accept 
even more economic pain in the short term 
it prescribed such bitter economic medicine as the removal of 
price controls on basic commodities while at the same time imposing 
wage controls on workers 
the study prepared by the international monetary fund and three 
other western economic organizations conceded that unemployment 
would rise in the short term and economic output which is already 
plummeting would fall further as inefficient industries are phased 
out 
however it said only a coldturkey approach to reform similar 
to the methods being used in poland would work in the soviet 
union 
the imperative is to make sufficient progress at the beginning 
so that reform is seen as an irreversible break with the past and 
the process gains an unstoppable momentum the study said 
but western experts noted that even the warsaw government has 
had trouble selling its austerity program with poles expressing 
their unhappiness in recent national elections and gorbachev does 
not start with the same base of popular support that the solidarity 
movement had in poland 
indeed the soviet president is having to battle with 15 restive 
republics who are tired of the central government botching the 
countrys economy and want more freedom to try their own formulas 
still us analysts were optimistic the soviets eventually will 
be able to embark on the radical reform proposed by the study 
which was begun last july at the direction of president bush and 
the leaders of japan germany britain france italy and canada 
ed hewett a soviet specialist at the brookings institution a 
washingtonbased research organization said that while the odds 
were low that the proposed reforms could be implemented 
immediately he would not rule out the chances that such changes 
could take hold within the next year 
hewett suggested it may take a true coalition government 
spanning the political spectrum with strong representation from the 
republics to push such a measure through 
while it may seem difficult to see how such a program could be 
implemented now politics in the soviet union is moving very fast 
and six months is a long time in soviet politics he said 
the 50page report supported bushs contention that large 
amounts of direct western aid should not be provided to the soviets 
until they begin implementing more fundamental reforms of their 
economy 
in the short term the report said western countries should 
emphasize providing technical assistance to the soviets in such 
areas as banking law and transportation 
it also said that targeted aid to help the soviets with 
environmental problems and the modernization of their energy 
production system would be useful 
the general recommendations of the report are recommendations 
that the united states will support and subscribe to secretary 
of state james a baker said his comment indicated that the 
document is likely to form the blueprint for western assistance to 
the soviets in the next year 
the study was ordered at the houston summit in an effort to 
break a deadlock between french and german leaders who were pushing 
for an immediate 15 billion aid package and the reluctance of bush 
and others to go along with that proposal 
the study said that without the implementation of a major and 
farreaching reform program direct western aid would be of 
little or no lasting value but it held out the promise that once 
the reforms were implemented such aid would be forthcoming 
the report was prepared by the 154nation international monetary 
fund and its sister organization the world bank the organization 
for economic cooperation and development and the european bank for 
reconstruction and development 
