<TEXT>
here in brief are the principal economic 
recommendations made friday by the international monetary fund and 
three other organizations in a report on reforming the soviet 
economy 
prices controls on prices must be removed quickly on many 
products in an effort to end shortages for certain key 
commodities the movement to market prices may need to be phased in 
over three years 
wages in order to insure that the initial spurt of prices does 
not trigger inflationary wage demands wages should be controlled 
in the early stages of price decontrol however the wage 
policy should provide a floor as well as a ceiling on employee 
wages 
money interest rates should be raised controls on bank credits 
to enterprises must be enforced and banks should have to hold a 
fraction of deposits as reserves on deposit with the central bank 
private ownership small firms should be privatized quickly 
through outright sales to infividuals cooperatives and others 
larger stateowned companies should have commercially oriented 
management with slower privatization perhaps through conversion of 
enterprises into joint stock companies owned by one of several 
state holding companies or owned through mutual funds 
social safety net policies are needed to deal with the rising 
unemployment that will occur as inefficient businesses are phased 
out and also provide protection for lowincome earners to 
compensate for the rising inflation once prices are decontrolled 
</TEXT>
