doubtful ideas and plans to pull the country out of its difficult 
situation 
the cia is gathering information on workers movements in the 
soviet union for its purposeful masterminding and funding 
antisoviet formations like radio stations that attack the 
soviet union he said 
kryuchkov did not say what kind of ideas he thought foreigners 
were trying to impose on the soviets he asked the 2250member 
parliament to give his agency more power to fight corruption and 
nationalist uprisings 
we will not avoid more serious consequences if we dont start 
immediately to fight destruction of our forces kryuchkov said 
we should be ready to accept bloodshed if we want to speak about 
bringing order to the country 
the speech similar to one kryuchkov gave earlier this month 
came as president mikhail s gorbachev struggles to maintain 
control over independenceminded republics simmering ethnic 
conflicts and a collapsing economy food shortages have hit moscow 
leningrad and other large cities prompting western countries to 
send emergency food 
fears of political turmoil were heightened with the surprise 
resignation thursday of foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze 
shevardnadze blamed reactionaries for moving the soviet union 
toward dictatorship and urged reformers to unite to preserve 
democratic changes 
the proposed constitutional amendments debated by the lawmakers 
would transform the soviet system of executive power into a 
presidential form of administration gorbachev wants more power to 
hold the country together and fight corruption while he carries out 
economic reform 
most legislators support the idea of strengthening 
presidential powers tass said 
opposition legislators belonging to the interregional group 
however said gorbachevs powers should be dependent on the 
approval of the supreme soviet legislature 
anatoly lukyanov chairman of the supreme soviet told the 
congress in a 20minute speech that the deputies should approve the 
amendments without reservation if parliament trusts the 
president it should untie his hands and not hold him on a rope of 
parliamentary debate lukyanov said 
he said preliminary voting on the amendments will begin monday 
kryuchkov said the kgb needs more authority to combat economic 
sabotage and nationalist militancy in the republics 
nationalists have assembled 26000 armed fighters in the soviet 
republics of estonia latvia armenia and georgia he said 
all 15 soviet republics have declared sovereignty in some form 
from the kremlin georgia lithuania estonia and lativa have 
declared outright independence 
in saying the country should be prepared for bloodshed 
kryuchkov referred to ethnic violence in some republics and asked 
isnt there bloodshed already 
boris yeltsin the reformist president of the russian 
federation dismissed kryuchkovs speech as old news 
yes there is sabotage yes there is corruption he said 
we have heard all this before 
a representative of the lithuanian government attending but not 
participating in the congress accused kryuchkov of using scare 
tactics that have failed before 
if he is speaking about bloodshed then it will be him who 
causes it said algis cekoulis 
hardline communists have urged gorbachev to impose a state of 
emergency in republics ridden by ethnic conflict and separatist 
movements gorbachev has said he might do that if the congress 
allows him to strengthen his hand in dealing with trouble spots 
kryuchkov also said he opposed private property laws that would 
let land fall into the hands of the black market and shady 
enterprises 
shevardnadzes unexpected resignation thursday pleased 
hardliners who opposed his role in negotiating the unification of 
germany and soviets role in the antiiraq coalition 
reformers have used his speech as a rallying cry a parade of 
speakers at the congress on friday echoed the 62yearold 
diplomats warning that hardliners were pushing the country toward 
a dictatorship 
gorbachev met friday for two hours with shevardnadze reportedly 
to discuss some way of keeping his longtime ally in the government 
it wasnt clear whether gorbachev intended to ask shevardnadze 
to continue as foreign minister or to take another post a 
shevardnadze aide said on thursday that the resignation was 
irreversible 
 
 
