the us education department last week placed 
new limits on minority college scholarships invoking civil rights 
law the department ruled that aid financed from a colleges own 
funds must be colorblind 
yet two months earlier in a far more liberal reading of those 
same statutes a regional office of the education department could 
find nothing wrong with harvard universitys giving admissions 
preference to offspring of alumni 
both rulings by the same federal agency expose an old truth 
about college admissions and scholarships laws and lofty 
principles may be invoked one day to support a desired social end 
only to be abandoned to suit another occasion 
confusion reigned last week over guidelines on racebased 
college scholarships colleges and civil rights groups generally 
reacted angrily to the bush administrations new rules forbidding 
the spending of institutional scholarship money to redress racial 
imbalances on campuses 
the ruling issued by the departments assistant secretary of 
civil rights michael l williams gave colleges and universities 
four years to comply with the new guidelines on minority 
scholarships 
nearly everyone including bush predicted a long struggle ahead 
in congress and the courts 
but over the years colleges and civil rights advocates have 
proven no more consistent in their principles than the government 
when it comes to promoting campus diversity or creating a level 
playing field in granting admissions and financial aid 
until the early 1960s colleges commonly used racial and ethnic 
quotas and perverted the financial aid process to limit the numbers 
of blacks jews and other minorities 
yale university bushs alma mater was among the most zealous 
of the ivy league institutions in using quotas and aid denials to 
keep their campus white christian and wealthy according to a 1985 
study joining the club by dan a oren 
last week many of the very colleges that had long used quotas 
and scholarships to exclude minority students were now invoking 
their right to establish goals for increasing the campus 
presence of blacks and others and to use racebased scholarships 
toward that end 
according to the college board 696 colleges and universities 
offered grants and scholarships based entirely on a students 
minority status in the 199091 school year 
the longsimmering dispute over the fairness of the scholastic 
aptitude test to minority students displays similar ephemeral 
patterns 
the sat was first used in 1926 when exclusionary quotas were 
the rule the idea was to create an objective measure to test the 
academic mettle of the collegebound to move at last toward an 
admissions process that was blind to all but a students merit 
yet civil rights and womens groups call the exam biased they 
claim that this test originally devised to open campus doors to 
the underprivileged is slamming them shut 
and those same civil rights groups that once yearned for a level 
playing field for minority applicants now can be heard demanding 
special advantages 
college admissions and scholarship policies have always been 
full of inconsistencies biases and illogic most admissions 
officials agree thats unavoidable after all students are being 
evaluated not machines 
and the admissions process aims to achieve many goals at once 
an academically capable student body yes but also a diverse one 
that includes blacks whites hispanics some superbrains some 
athletes perhaps a cellist or two 
the goal of ethnic and racial diversity doesnt always mesh 
perfectly with fairness in the awarding of scholarships and 
thats where disputes like last weeks arise 
the latest debate began because an assistant education secretary 
ingenuously tried to lend an element of consistency to the awarding 
of scholarships by applying a strict constructionist interpretation 
of civil rights law 
but history suggests that such efforts to tidy up this 
inherently sloppy business of scholarships arent necessarily 
welcomed or needed 
equals 
