<TEXT>
here is the text of the philadelphia 
inquirers editorial in sundays editions headlined an 
apology and subtitled the editorial on norplant and poverty 
was misguided and wrongheaded 
 
its rare that we regret publishing an editorial from almost the 
moment it appears in print and its rarer still that we feel the 
need to apologize to our readers for a misguided and wrongheaded 
editorial opinion but such is the case with the editorial that 
appeared in this space on dec 12 entitled norplant and 
poverty great pain anger and controversy have resulted from 
that editorial and we deeply regret our decision to print it 
among the people who were incensed by the editorial were many of 
the inquirers own reporters editors and members of the editorial 
board in the days since it appeared we have been doing a lot of 
listening and soulsearching 
we realize now that we hastily and foolishly juxtaposed two news 
items that appeared in the inquirer the previous day federal 
approval of the longterm contraceptive norplant and the release of 
a research groups report that said nearly half of black children 
are living in poverty and that the situation is getting worse with 
time the editorial posed the question of whether encouraging women 
who are on welfare to use norplant could help reverse this bleak 
trend 
where did we go wrong lets begin with the headline which 
asked whether contraception could reduce the underclass and 
thus aroused peoples fears of something far worse than promoting 
birth control later we used the word eugenics as a way of 
explaining what we didnt mean but it only inflamed matters more 
most fundamentally in linking the issues of race and 
contraception we left too many people with the impression that our 
cure for poverty was to reduce the number of black people although 
that certainly was not what we meant to suggest the fact that so 
many people interpreted it that way is a clear indication that the 
editorial was fatally flawed therefore we failed in our effort to 
provoke thoughtful discussion on the issue of birth control and 
poverty 
its true that many single young women lessen their chances of 
escaping poverty by having children too early in life but its 
also true that the very hopelessness of their circumstances often 
underlies the decision not to postpone childbearing creating hope 
where none now exists must be the main tenet of any effective war 
on poverty 
in the previous editorial we said that women on welfare should 
be encouraged but not compelled to use norplant we suggested 
incentives such as an additional benefit of some kind our critics 
countered that to dangle cash or some other benefit in front of a 
desperately poor woman is tantamount to coercion theyre right 
we still believe that this new form of reliable birth control 
which is likely to have wide appeal to middleclass women should 
be equally available to poor women who want to use it but we also 
realize and should have been even clearer about it that this 
has to be a matter of personal choice we dont seek to limit the 
options of poor women but to empower them 
we remain committed to a whole host of strategies for reducing 
poverty from better schools to job training to radical welfare 
reform we think education about birth control is important and if 
norplant lives up to its advance billing it could be helpful to 
many women 
and we wish we had said it that way to begin with the earlier 
norplant editorial undercut our credibility and our efforts to be a 
thoughtful responsible and compassionate voice on the complex 
issues of poverty we apologize to those we hurt and offended 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901222-0085 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lech walesa who led solidaritys 10year 
struggle to depose communist rule took the oath saturday as his 
nations first popularly elected president and declared poland 
finally free of foreign domination 
the 47yearold labor activist a peasants son who was educated 
to repair machinery pointedly excluded his communist predecessor 
from the swearingin ceremony before parliament 
he pledged that poland would become a stable element in a 
peaceful europe seek friendly relations with its neighbors and 
continue the dramatic market reforms started by the government of 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki who walesa defeated in the 
elections 
walesas swearingin came a decade after he led the shipyard 
strike that created the east blocs first independent trade union 
and one year since he put together its first noncommunist 
government 
i solemnly swear to the polish people that i will be faithful 
to constitutional decisions i will protect the dignity of the 
nation the sovereignty and security of the state said walesa in 
a clear voice holding up his right hand 
his wife danuta stood solemnly at his side 
walesa did not invite president wojciech jaruzelski the 
longtime communist leader who imposed martial law to crush 
solidarity in 1981 and imprisoned walesa for nearly a year 
present instead of jaruzelski was ryszard kaczorowski president 
of the anticommunist governmentinexile in london the 
governmentinexile was set up after the prewar warsaw government 
was forced to flee the nazis in 1939 
kaczorowski 71 was received as a head of state as he returned 
to his homeland for the first time on a specially dispatched 
government plane 
handing over the presidential insignia seals handwritten 
constitution and other symbols of prewar authority in the gilded 
royal castle kaczorowski said the governmentinexile had 
fulfilled its mission and could now cease to exist 
walesa also accepted the blessing of the church a mass was 
scheduled in his honor by the roman catholic primate cardinal 
jozef glemp 
hundreds of people chanting our president our president 
lined the narrow cobblestone lanes of the old town when walesa 
walked the short distance from the castle to st johns athedral 
he raised his hand in his familiar vforvictory sign made 
famous during solidaritys struggle 
in his inaugural speech walesa said the evil era when the 
authorities of our country were appointed under pressure of 
foreigners or as the result of forced compromises is ending 
poland has known only 21 years of full independence since it was 
partitioned in 1795 it was reconstituted as the second republic in 
1918 only to fall under german and then sovietimposed communist 
rule for 50 years until solidarity took over the government in 
1989 jaruzelski remained as president under a negotiated deal he 
stepped down early to make way for new elections 
walesa pledged poland now would become an element of the 
peaceful order in europe he said it seeks good relations with 
germany and its neighbors to the east lithuania ukraine 
byelorussia and russia he did not mention the soviet union 
he told poles that saturday was the beginning of the third 
polish republic but that they must believe in themselves 
passivity and apathy these are the biggest obstacles on the 
road toward the wellbeing of poles the president said when 
we start to work with confidence the most developed countries will 
show more interest in us as well 
