<TEXT>
like farmers all over china this 
year ma ziwen reaped one of his best wheat crops ever but the 
bumper harvest has brought disappointment for ma and problems for 
the government 
the official media for months have been filled with reports of a 
bountiful grain harvest from the high plateaus of tibet where 
barley is grown to the fertile rice paddies of the southeast 
the crops were so plentiful that free market prices tumbled 
that meant ma a young farmer in northern chinas ningxia hui 
autonomous region lost the profits he expected from farming 10 
extra acres this year hed hoped to earn enough to buy a bicycle 
for the government the harvest is like a goodnews badnews 
joke it had mounted a major campaign this year to increase grain 
production and organized peasant brigades to irrigate more 
farmland 
but it found it lacked money to buy the harvest and facilities 
to store it 
the situation is not as severe as in the soviet union where 
distribution problems are expected to lead to widespread hunger 
this winter despite a record grain harvest but china does stand to 
lose much of the extra grain to spoilage 
one official estimate is that 42 million tons are lost every 
year because of poor storage facilities this year the loss likely 
will be higher because 33 million to 44 million tons of the 462 
million ton harvest are being stored outdoors 
china last year reaped 448 million tons equaling a 1984 record 
most of chinas grain is sold to the state under contracts that 
farmers sign individually each spring they are free to sell 
anything they produce over contract on chinas small free market 
but this years big supply caused free market prices to fall ma 
said he had hoped to get 1300 yuan or 250 for the 2200 pounds 
of grain he had left after fulfilling his contract instead free 
market buyers offered 820 yuan 160 
meanwhile the grain keeps flooding in 
in late november more than a month after the harvest farmers 
still were bringing loads to ningxias hexi township granary even 
though it had long since been filled granary workers said 
the nearby tongxin county granary stopped buying after it filled 
its warehouse in late october said granary director yang hanyu 
thats exactly what beijing wants to avoid it has ordered local 
grain bureaus to buy all grain if farmers do not want to sell their 
extra crops on the free market the government promised loans from 
the central bank to pay the bills but the money has been slow in 
coming 
the government fears social unrest in the countryside if farmers 
take heavy financial losses it also fears farmers will refuse en 
masse to plant as much grain next year and instead choose 
highprofit crops such as tobacco 
with the population at 113 billion and growing 15 percent 
annually the government says china must produce at least 500 
million tons by the year 2000 just to keep pace 
china imported 14 million tons of grain this year much of it 
from the united states but hopes to become selfsufficient 
increasing the harvest is not as easy as this years bumper crop 
made it look although the state increased spending on agriculture 
by 496 million or nearly 8 percent officials acknowledge a key 
reason for the good harvest was unusually good weather 
in order to make significant longterm gains the state would 
have to reorganize its agricultural system something that could 
be politically as well as economically difficult 
it would mean replacing the millions of tiny family farm plots 
with farms large enough to use heavy machinery and wellmanaged 
enough to use advanced technology it would also mean raising 
returns to farmers 
