<TEXT>
the emigration of soviet jews to israel peaked 
in a weekend airlift with an average of 100 newcomers arriving 
every hour news reports said 
israel television reported that from thursday night to saturday 
morning 5500 soviet jews arrived and another 1500 were expected 
on eight flights by early sunday 
a spokesman for the quasigovernmental jewish agency which 
handles immigrant transportation could not immediately confirm the 
figures 
israeli officials have said the upsurge of immigration was due 
to fears of political instability in the soviet union this was 
exacerbated by the resignation on thursday of foreign minister 
eduard shevardnadze who warned the country was sliding into 
dictatorship 
they also cite the economic crisis in the soviet union and 
improved transportation arrangements that allow jews to fly out of 
the former soviet bloc capitals 
on saturday the jewish sabbath the government waived a ban on 
flights and ordered the national carrier el al to use every plane 
available to ferry the jews from eastern europe 
officials expect more than 30000 soviet arrivals in december 
bringing the years total to about 200000 that figure includes 
jewish immigrants from ethiopia and elsewhere 
in 1949 the biggest year of immigration in israel 240000 jews 
arrived officials expect 1991 to be the biggest year of 
immigration to israel 
israels population of 47 million does not include 17 million 
palestinians and 100000 jewish settlers living in the occupied 
territories 
palestinians are worried the emigres will be used to colonize 
the occupied territories he israeli government recently announced 
plans to build new housing for soviet arrivals in arab east 
jerusalem 
the pace of immigration is causing housing shortages and 
unemployment among the immigrants israeli officials are fearful 
the thousands arriving also will overwhelm schools and social 
services 
in tokyo the new un high commissioner for refugees said 
saturday there are concerns of a mass exodus from the soviet union 
as problems mount there 
i hope not but theres a great concern among the europeans 
said sadako ogata a ustrained professor and specialist in human 
rights 
she added that some officials in japan are also closely watching 
the soviet emigre situation because of the proximity of the two 
nations 
you have to recognize were neighbors she said 
mrs ogata 63 replaces thorvald stoltenberg who recently 
resigned to become deputy prime minister of norway 
