drug traffickers saturday said the 
united states has no right to judge colombias government for 
allegedly taking a softer stance in its war on the cocaine trade 
the medellin cocaine cartel using its pseudonym the 
extraditables made its statements in a letter addressed to the 
us ambassador in colombia thomas mcnamara a copy of the letter 
was sent by fascimile mail to news organizations 
president carlos gavirias new strategy entails ending 
extraditions to the united states and giving reduced sentences to 
cocaine traffickers who surrender and confess on tuesday reputed 
medellin leader fabio ochoa surrendered to authorities 
us officials have expressed concern the new policy may hurt 
regional antidrug efforts and the traffickers letter was 
apparently in response to the us reaction 
the traffickers statement said the us officials are the 
only ones in the world who negotiate with drug traffickers the 
traffickers said while colombian drug offenders are given the 
harshest treatment in us jails some american smugglers serve no 
time 
the letter mentioned barry seal a us trafficker turned 
government informant as an example of an american criminal who 
never knew the jails of the united states 
after helping the drug enforcement administration indict several 
major cocaine traffickers seal was assassinated by the colombian 
drug mafia in 1986 
among those accused of having ordered his murder is ochoa 
drug bosses have said as many as 300 cocaine smugglers are 
willing to surrender in return for more legal guarantees 
thousands of colombians have died since august 1989 in 
drugrelated violence ranging from gunfights to bombings to 
political assassinations the killing that august of antidrug 
crusader luis galan a leading presidential contender prompted the 
governments war on drug traffickers 
the extraditables also criticized gavirias new drug strategy as 
part of a policy of repression against drug trafficking because 
it requires smugglers to confess crimes 
the drug barons say requiring citizens to incriminate themselves 
in court is unconstitutional 
gaviria in comments published saturday said his drug policy 
was not a deal with traffickers but an attempt to solve the drug 
problem within the framework of colombian justice 
we are as committed as we ever were to the fight against drug 
trafficking the washington post quoted gaviria as saying 
