alleged interatom gave iraq sensitive nuclear training and 
equipment 
interatom and its owner the giant electronics conglomerate 
siemens denied the magazines report interatom specializes in 
atomic energy plant construction and uranium enrichment but is 
also involved in nonnuclear engineering 
franzen said the information from the us list is of varying 
quality and some firms are included which are completely above 
suspicion but he said in other cases further investigation is 
needed 
if german firms are found to have violated the embargo they 
could face charges in germany of breaking the countrys export 
laws 
der spiegel magazine said the list of alleged german 
embargobusters resulted from us monitoring of iraqi telephone 
and telefax communications 
us officials are informed of iraqs supply plans because 
american intelligence listens in on iraqs overall telephone 
traffic and intercepts telefax messages the magazine said 
without identifying its sources 
in another export scandal in 1988 us intelligence said german 
companies helped libya build a factory allegedly for making 
chemical weapons the german government at first rejected the 
allegations but later acknowledged they were true 
as a result of that scandal the head of a german chemical firm 
was convicted of breaking the countrys export laws 
